In mathematics, the '''actuarial polynomials''' ''a''{{su|b=''n''|p=(β)}}(''x'') are polynomials studied by {{harvtxt|Toscano|1950}} given by the [[generating function]]

:<math>\displaystyle \sum_n \frac{a_n^{(\beta)}(x)}{n!}t^n = \exp(\beta t +x(1-e^t))</math>

{{harv|Roman|1984|loc=4.3.4}}, {{harvtxt|Boas|Buck|1958}}.

