In [[queueing theory]], a discipline within the mathematical [[probability theory|theory of probability]], a '''retrial queue''' is a model of a system with finite capacity, where jobs which arrive and find the system busy wait for some time before trying again to enter the system. Examples of such systems include making restaurant reservations and [[packet switching]] networks.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Yang | first1 = Tao | last2 = Templeton | first2 = J. G. C. | year = 1987 | title = A survey on retrial queues | journal = [[Queueing Systems]] | volume = 2 | issue = 3 | pages = 201-233 | publisher = [[Kluwer Academic Publishers]] | doi = 10.1007/BF01158899}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last1 = Artalejo | first1 = Jesús R.  | last2 = Gómez-Corral | first2 = Antonio | year = 2008 | title = Retrial Queueing Systems: A Computational Approach | isbn = 978-3-540-78724-2 | doi = 10.1007/978-3-540-78725-9 | publisher = [[Springer Berlin Heidelberg]]}}</ref>

